A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
The Republican leaders justify their policy with the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by reaffirming that election fraud in the United States is less than the number of people killed by lightning.
Incidentally, Republican lawyers in the United States have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the vote.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. federal states are responsible for the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, the majority of American governments have announced new laws since 2009 which make the registration procedure difficult.
Following the November 2010 elections, this phenomenon has gained in importance, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states being listed.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of electoral rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of US citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce the time-limits for early voting, invalidate the right to register as voters on the day of the election, and give citizens the right to vote for which a legal act is available.
Before the 2006 elections, no US Member State has requested voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of the law of Indiana in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other countries.
Over the past two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states that force voters to present a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal ID card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million electors, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a certificate.
However, often more than a hundred dollars are to be paid to obtain the necessary ID card.
The new restrictions affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes disproportionately.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people with income less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the necessary photo ID.
That is enough further.
The students who are regarded as voters, who increase their voice for democratic candidates, are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several countries.
On the other hand, the same States allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state called for a proof of citizenship for the election.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws calling on voters to prove their American citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic votes.
It is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, Republican legislators in 2011 promoted laws in eight states that abolished the registration of voters on the election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to assist those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, campaigns to register voters in the 2004 general elections have contributed to the registration of some 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters registered in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period of premature voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who have chosen in advance were African-Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who have chosen in advance.
In contrast, the whites, representing 76% of the voters, represented only 46% of the voters who chose in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Attorney General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
However, the newly introduced rules in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of electoral rights difficult.
The democratic critics advocate the party political nature of the passed laws and see in them as a clear goal the influence of the results in the 2012 decisive states.
A 2011 report from the Brennan Center shows that those states that have passed these laws make 171 of the 270 votes required by the electoral panel to win the presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these changes to the electoral system legislation will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the vote.
In this sense, these measures partially undermine the democratic system of the United States.
