Analyze the Higgs Boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs Boson has aroused a certain appearance last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of the nature and behaviour of matter - but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists it's not completely certain that it's really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is much like the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics convention in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be completely sure about it.
Nevertheless, we assume that this is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let's look at what it is about.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects not to be present at the same place at the same time.
It's not possible to violate this rule - and don't try it too hard because you're getting hurt.
Because even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to them: the Pauli exclusion principle, which means that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantity state", which consists largely of some of their characteristics.
From this the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione, who obey the Pauli principle in a similar way.
And in the other, the Bosons are moving, a bad band of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure, these Bosons are divided into two groups: the Mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs Boson would somehow be related.
But it must be stressed here that these bosons are not all so exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "bote" of the electromagnetic force.
If a particle speeds up with an electric charge or changes direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this place, like a pebble thrown into a pond.
This "disruption" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "disturbed" to show this Boson.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be torn by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is needed - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, they are not all particles and not all materials interacting with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself on the fridge.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (as well as the photos) have no mass.
For what can all these research be "good", Mrs. Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to review the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to examine carefully all deviations between observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes in the model.
One has to say that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not explain the gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that makes up about 80% of the matter of the universe (new ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there was no such thing.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulses) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was regarded at the beginning as a "laboratory".
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also be based on all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, in 1969, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in the optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has presented it with the 2009 Nobel Prize for Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you really can never know it...
