"For six months three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients less than 45 years old," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the home Victor Gadbois come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
The issue of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to care to relieve the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the end stage of their life, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor Gadbois home and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in Montreal, are more or less exclusively specializing in the care of cancer patients.
Just this great inadequacy in Quebec’s healthcare system ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care face the adoption of a law regulating death aid and assisted suicide with concerns.
Since the month of October, a manifesto in circulation has been signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that all have a right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to death support.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days of great pain in the emergency room without taking measures to relieve them.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologens treat their patients distended to the last day despite the worst predictions.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were minimal when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my onkologin that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she regretted that I was giving up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the caregiver that it has not allowed this request after their pains have been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the society of domestic palliative care of the Montreal metropolitan area, 8% of patients do not speak of pain treatment.
Thus, at the very end of life, doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which requires that the patient be either sporadic or permanent until his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pains are not eased all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me to sleep," but "I want my pain to be eased".
