A Constitution With the Breaking Bar in Egypt
It's a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more than ever divided over the constitutional declaration which temporarily grants it unlimited authority, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version on the next day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State had given this House two additional months to complete his work.
Egypt has been relying for almost two years on a provisional, multi-modal text, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only led to an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step right with feet".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time, which forces the brothers to refrain from their attempt to explain the passage by section to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way of identifying his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is lingering throughout the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote well.
As far as the Egyptian people are concerned, with this withdrawal of an overcrowded vote, an ultimatum is put: "either you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited power of attorney," the latter should, after the adoption of the Constitution, supposedly end.
85, mostly Islamic members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they have turned away because they believe that they have not been able to bring their views into effect.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to reach the quorum, 11 people were added yesterday morning, in the hurry of 11 people, deputy members.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were generally adopted unanimously.
The commentators found it entertaining, by the way, that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the panel believed that the pendulum was not exactly the case of the constitutional assembly.
The text, which was adopted yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, remains finally identical with that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is evidence of their good will and respect for the other members of the Egyptian society.
"Pleasant Holiness" responds to the liberals, who regard this only as a propaganda strike.
Because they believe that the Constitution is being Islamized by other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, particularly in relation to the verification of compliance with the laws of Sharia.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is alarming, as "those who are asked to comment have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the one we are now.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system," said Alexis Bluet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admits, however, "that there may be a ambiguity in the context of Article 220, since the terms used are rejected in the religious vocabulary.
It refers in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, note d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised about the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide."
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
Moslem brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another issue: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Similarly, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as requested by the human rights defence associations.
The latter also share their fears about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
Blasphemy's reality is being maintained, and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to free speech, especially for the press.
In addition, no longer refers to the protection of women, Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch emphasizes.
In their view, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy places, the navel of the world and a sea of Sole
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and unspoiled nature.
AIF identifies you as the five most important reasons for a visit to Israel.
Overcoming the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine on a wedding feast, walking on the water, the closure of the sea storm and the fishing.
Jesus also appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most sanctuaries, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers go the path of suffering or the crossroads of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretoria, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the Graves Church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion site, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to the Christian view, is the navel of the world, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem is also the most holy place of the Jews - the wall of complaint, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Traditionally, people of different denominations leave note there with wishes that are then fulfilled.
A trip to the heights
The ruins of the fortress Massada form the remains of the secret hiding place from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in 25 AD.
They lie on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins of their own strength.
All others take an air cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an old legend, supposedly pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visit Unique Museums
In this country there are almost 300 museums.
Not everyone can be visited on a trip alone.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Parliament.
Old Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in caves in the Judean desert, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits are kept there.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the Museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the visitors and bathers at the time.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Entrance is free, and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most comprehensive department is the memorial to the children built to commemorate the 1.5 million children destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
The stars sparkle.
And it sounds like the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Doing Something for Health
The three main recreational areas of Israel lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of the three places has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and there is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmer problem-free on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sun) and sludge, as well as for treating inflammation of the skin, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and for the calming of tightened nerves.
Touch the Secrets of Ancientity
These secrets are the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city, the famous sea route, Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, was connected.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to traditions, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he led a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after the constellation.
Fortuna shall be the legend of all the team who touch the walls of the street with their star sign.
In Jaffa you can find newly remarried couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusades.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Today, evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Favourites for tourists
When you go to Israel, do not worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of the Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is not taken into euros, but into dollars that can simply be changed in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you usually get on the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a high-speed train and in Haifa there is the only underground line of the country with six stations connecting the suburb to the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground roller coaster.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which covers including switching for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to the sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed, and public transport is resting.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without sheds and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between various dishes with lamb and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus pasta, various sauces, fried balls of pure beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
For this there are many well-nourished cats that stroll comfortably and unspoiledly through the streets.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to delicacies.
Depending on the brand, a car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost on average 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and rest seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, which represents an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 period, before removing the visa obligation on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While Members of Parliament and citizens' lawyers discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals already deal with counterfeit certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Its only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families remaining in the home.
On 1 December, a law came into force requiring every migrant worker to pass a test proving knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants who wish to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail.
However, in the future, the tests will be mandatory for all guest workers, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
In doing so, you need not only to test language, but also to test Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the maintenance and the extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which the Russian language is the official language.
It also excludes persons who received their training certificates and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Purpose, problem and protection of rights
The totality of the exams will be under the aegis of the Puschkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; already more than 160 centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
However, before the entry into force of the law in the press, citizens' lawyers asked several times the following question: What does this really mean?
What changes does the requirement to display language skills bring to both Russians and guest workers?
Above all, against speakers of the Migration Authority, it is important to reduce the number of forced labourers.
"Many people now talk about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelew, Head of Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must already be protected before they leave.
Only organized recruitment will solve 90% the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without work, education, language skills and medical evaluation.
Sebelew is convinced that a future migrant will inevitably encounter people with bad intentions, who will put him under the pretext of helping him into a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure with dozens of his like months without food and documents and will spend 12 to 14 hours in the day.
Many complaints from our migrants reach us.
"In your home country, the one is promised to you, and upon arrival you will be betrayed, their passports will be taken off and will not receive the promised wage," confirmed Tolib Schwaripow, head of the Department of Labour Migration of the Tajikistan Migration Authority.
Don't smear, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot only master the language of the target country but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: Only a few Turks, Uzbeken and Tadschiken can afford a reasonable basic education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothing, shoes and things to do with school.
As a teenager, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Citizens stress the following important aspects of the law.
The test only needs to be performed by legal migrants.
If you do not have this status, there is no exam and therefore no official work.
In the meantime, most of the guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcomed by heart" or "No access for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely falsified and we are not registered, and this results in cases of extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tajik Umed Huschkadamow to journalists.
"Only spare no cost of wrong papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can have been falsified.
Some fake certificates that confirm the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The falsified papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not receive it for nothing: Every migrant who hoped to save his tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important direct task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be purchased simply is a matter of agreement between officials and civil society lawyers.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they are given time for a language course.
In addition, new arrivals are offered in areas where there is no need for active communication with people without language skills.
Interior Ministry Ignores Illegal Arms Market
Share of legal weapons in crime very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning a tightening up of the Arms Act for private arms owners.
The authorities thus respond to recent events: injured at shootings at weddings as well as seven deaths at the Amok Run of Moscow's lawyer Dmitri Winogradow.
Police want to ban the wearing of non-lethal weapons in public and raise the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal supported and promised the Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, Irina Jarowaja, that the changes to the Arms Act will be presented shortly to the Duma.
Not all are satisfied that the Russian authorities want to tackle the problems by "drawing the screws".
An open letter was published on the Internet, whose author - representatives of various arms associations - asks the authorities to refrain from "senseless tightening".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very small, said the criminal attorney, Wasilij Lesnikow, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed during the course of six months in 2012, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening the law will not prevent private arms owners from using criminals on the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors, in Moscow you can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the spread of illegal weapons is under control.
Supplier: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, says a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and in the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts weapons orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," Baranez says.
In the second channel, illegal weapons are being stolen from criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen from both the arms chambers of the police and directly from law enforcement personnel.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
In many military camps explosions often occurred.
"There is evidence that in some cases it was arson to hide the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, weapons producers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not withstand international competition and therefore hide the weapons under hand on the black market, for example in Moscow," says the expert.
Another channel of the black market is the smuggler.
Many pistols and rifles come from poor countries such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is its own, sometimes handcrafted production as well as a mafia that organizes the smuggling," the former military member explains.
Where did the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels in the supply of illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Problem Analysis Centre and the State administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminological Literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to the investigators, the majority of the illegal weapons originate from the army and the law enforcement authorities.
Half of all the weapons on the black market were there because of the "indebtedness of those responsible who have come to deal with weapons in their work," says the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from thefts in the production of weapons, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant to a gun store who does not want to be named by name ensures that weapons found in illegal excavations have not been bought for a long time since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more often for dealers to get the supply in a weapons warehouse.
A gun, for example a gun of type TT, is purchased via a handgun.
The weapon is displayed and handed over by the fence.
"The dealer takes the gun to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, are aware of everything and therefore, if they are unable to comply with the plan to detect crime, carry out periodic checks on dealers who offer illegal weapons," the sales consultant adds.
"Like in luxury store"
Buyers and sellers find most of the information about acquaintances with each other.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested to me come to the "Begowaja" station, where a person would wait for me, which brought me to a certain place, where we could then negotiate the price.
