Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the Member States of the European Space Agency, Poland was taken up as the 20th member of this Space Agency. Poland is thus the second member country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008.
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The road of Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish Cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, but they did not always come up with understanding.
I recall here, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work on "the entrance to the cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix Rep-Hirsch, founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "entry to the cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important defender of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to space development was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the face of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the design and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the draisine.
The information for this purpose comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933 the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered shots.
The research carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrychiegi.
It is clear from the documents submitted that research has been carried out up to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the technical press of the design by Ing. Rohoziński showed a photoelectric hunting dragon, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda povietzrzna i rakitobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitte Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of activity his work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space travel were published in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space travel are dedicated.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space company.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was clear that the exploration of space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became an ordinary member already in autumn 1956.
In the following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became deputy chairman of the International Federation of Space Administration.
He was in office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been a major player in the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first start took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959, flight tests started in the Błędów desert with the two-stage rocket RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another level of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for monitoring altitude winds.
However, further development was discontinued in 1962.
Following the first RM rockets, the Meteor-1 rocket was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and its initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of rocket were developed (meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket has a 0.4 liter capacity transport space, Meteor-1B more than 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C more than 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km at all three types.
In the years 1965 to 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had an initial weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to a height of approximately 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which followed the establishment of a national COSPAR Committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the Czech pilot Vladimir Remek second intercosmonaut.
