The movie Argo: If it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrative Islamist students occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they demanded the delivery of the overthrown Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had preserved the patronage over his regime for decades.
For the American government there was no positive way out of this situation - she could not afford to throw the shawl overboard, as this would have greatly damaged the trust of her allies in other countries.
At the same time, she was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt of the liberation of the hostages made everything worse.
The diplomats who were captured were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been arranged by the Algerian Government.
The fate of the hostages evoked at home a wave of solidarity as well as anti-Iranian sentiments.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo by director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the United States a small victory.
Immediately before the arrival of the message, six ambassadors managed to flee.
This ended after many complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story of their true identity - they traveled with Canadian passports bound as members of a film staff who allegedly visited film locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by the expert for "Exfiltration", Tony Mendez, also required Hollywood collaboration.
To make the tarnation credible, the article on this film project appeared in specialist journals, there were press conferences held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time, based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful housekeeper's play, such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
This changes the mood levels in the film - on one side the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no major differences).
On the other hand, the loose passages from Hollywood, which are ironic and slightly over-peeled, are coming.
And then there are the scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the halls, on the telephone...
Ben Affleck has achieved a remarkable restart in his career with this film.
From a smiled actor has become a respectable director, and also as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Crimea No Children's Game (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City Without Grace (2010).
At the same time it is Affleck's first film that does not play in the home Boston director's Boston film.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
But Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that have really taken place - the entrance sequence of the indignation of the message is very impressive in its clarity, and nevertheless conveys the feeling of confusion and unforeseeableness that occurs when history moves somewhere.
Affleck also performs a similar effect with his team on fictional scenes (the false film staff on a bassoon in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the few, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little - which then doesn't always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is turned away from a telephone call in America, or also the persecution hunt on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its all too wide spread, which is required by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters would have earned more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck’s film thereby loses a bit of traction. It’s a film that you can track with a certain interest and goldize the design and the retro style reminiscent of a 70th-year-old thriller.
However, it is difficult to arouse enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history living to this day in a certain way and as a proof of how the notions of the almighty and all-knowing secret services are superior, it is sufficient.
