For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health when carrying 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is Hell, and others work in Hell literally.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by bringing sulfur from the volcano Kawah Ijen in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this he must rise every day down to the ground of his crater, where the sulfurous gas flowing from the earth in contact with the air is fortified.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the wasted paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent in the turtle's pace, keeping the balance and carefully setting their steps so that they do not slip out and fall off.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocent for every kilo of sulphur they mine.
Upstairs, they pave the way between the tourists who photograph them like circus coffees and run with the tiringly heavy baskets three kilometers to the scale, which a mining company has placed a little further down at an altitude of 1850 meters
The company is PT Candi Nagrimbi, who has since 1960 exploited the incidences in the volcano and (no better said) his workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) each, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"Since we usually carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each route," Anto explains to us, who usually makes three routes a day.
He needs three hours for each route, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros).
What looks like a miserable wage for such a seemingly inhumane effort, but is the triple of what he would earn with fieldwork.
"The daily wage of mine workers here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid on the day at the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros) is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) on the day, and the work was not as hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, for a reason as important as the sulfur in Indonesia: "I have married a girl from Bali where they are Hindus, and I have brought them to Java to convert them to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
For the past three years, 27-year-old Anto has been putting his life on the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already left him the first traces, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
