On questions relating to the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day only the image of the Presidential Meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private meeting, limited audio".
The few information circulated among the journalists was received by the press spokesmen of some of the unaseur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesperson.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused discomfort to the hundreds of journalists of various national and international media who demanded more information.
Afterwards, the Presidential Office of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "Declaration" of the summit, but this was the explanation of Humala and not the official document at the end of the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite a strong call by the press, the so-called Lima declaration that had been announced earlier was also not published.
On the official website of the ASPA, one can be sure that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but to a large extent they restricted access to information.
