Few in Puerto Rico have such a large spiritual collection of the history of the country's basketball as Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
Before being tied to the wheelchair by a stroke in 2008, Rexes was part of this sport for six years, whether as players of lower classes, players of the first national league, proxy and head of the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or President of the Basketball Association.
"For my life I set up a lot of hats in basketball, even several at the same time as I was president of the BSN, head of the national team and president of the Federation in the 1990s," Reyes remembered when visiting Primera Hora at his home in Bayamón, where he lived with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball was my life."
Reyes does not exaggerate with this statement.
The walls of his house are almost all decorated with photos and memories of his long career and testify to them.
Bayamón in the heart
The most emotional memories are those of his time at the Vaqueros from the mid-50s as a player to 1982, where he celebrated his 15th anniversary as co-director or managing director of the club.
"These were my best years that I enjoyed most, because I was allowed to be part of eight of the Vaqueros championships since 1967 as managing director, co-manager or trainer.
