Larry Hagman, whose role as the J.R. Ewing oil magnate in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned as J.R. this year in a new season of "Dallas", died on Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birth town of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role that most liked him," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of the harvest Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, said her publisher Jeffrey Lane.
He made all the joys he knew.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life in full accord," explained Gray in a communication.
Hagman was diagnosed with liver cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he drank a lot over the years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he underwent transplantation.
In the years before "Dallas" Hagman became known on television as a nice guy in the years 1965 to 1970 with the Sitcom "Improving Jeannie" of the NBC television company.
There he played astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is put on his head when he meets an attractive "Jinn" (played by Barbara Eden), who will live with him at home.
He was also an actor of two comedies who were broadcast only for a short time, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His cinematographic works included well-rated roles in "The Group", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchantingly abominable J.R. who made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of CBS television chain over the Ewing-Clan and other figures around it was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
